      "date": "2013-07-29 08:49:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nCould you explain how you reproduce this error?\n\nll_data_version(), on restore, will and need to be done on the volatile file. The Layout Lock is held on the regular file, which has a RELEASE layout. There is no way getattr is sent to OFD, has the OST IDs were discarded when the file was released.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d877895c78e525a7e883591c4e333f90f342b0fb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-29 17:33:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\nI used two clients: one as an agent and another one as normal client, and on the normal client, I just release and restore one file. On the 2nd try, it hung at restoring the file.\n\nFrom what I have seen, the agent client served the restore request and copied file back to lustre, then it called copy_end ioctl to send progress REQ back to MDT. However, it was returned with ENOENT when trying to get data_version(this is because ll_data_version() doesn't refresh layout so it used stale layout to send getattr REQ to OFD), then coordinator received this error and refused to release layout.\n\nTaking a step back, even ll_data_version() were implemented correctly by refreshing layout, it wouldn't work also because the layout was already taken by restoring REQ, so there is no way for it to get one.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
